segments.text: They would suggest that so-and-so needed to be on the bowling team or so-and-so needed to be on the music committee at the MSC or on SCONA or you need to run for freshman class treasurer or vice president.
And then they would tell you, now here's the way you do it.

or if it was an intramural we would get out and work out they'd work with the team on plays and how to succeed at athletics or at student recreational activities on campus or in the MSC so I was encouraged to go to every dorm
and go in every freshman's room and whip out and spend a few minutes and remember their name, what their major was, and where they were from, their hometown.
Now this was in terms of- This is in the fall because the freshman officers ran then in the spring.

So during that first semester, of course, I'd been there in summer school, so some of the newness that everybody else was faced with, at least I was a little bit oriented to the environment, not to the core, but where things were and how to expedite certain activities.
But that's what they told me to do, and I did.
And so I got involved through that activity and then the entomology club over in the department and the church and a number of things that were not directly A&M related.
Did you put up signs?
No.
And did... Don't ever remember any during...
55 through 59 by advertising.
You went around and introduced yourself.
People knew everybody.
And so you didn't have a rally, you didn't have a... Nope.
We just went around just like the old politicians I guess used to and introduced yourself and visited with people and told them what you were concerned about and what you were going to do.
And they made up their mind as to who they liked the best.
Do you remember what your concerns were that freshman year?
What you might have told them you were concerned about?
No, I don't.
And what was the vote?
Do you remember how close it was?
It was fairly close.
As I remember, Joe Bueser was one of my opponents.
And I believe Fish Fudge was the other one.
But it was... Alright, and then when you were elected, did that change your status in your outfit?
No.
You still had to...
I still had to hit a brace.
Still had to wipe the buzzes off.
Still had to do push-ups.
Still had to shine...
Senior shoes and junior shoes.
Do you remember?
I didn't have a problem when we had activities, you know, when we had a meeting to plan the freshman ball or to leave.
I just simply had to ask the first sergeant for a pass.
Who did you work with as a freshman president?
Primarily Dean Penberthy and Mr. Hardesty, Pete Hardesty.
Forgot Hardesty, yeah.
And what were the big events?
Freshman ball.
Freshman ball.
The dance and everything.
Describe it.
Well, we had a band, and we had girls mostly from TSCW, and that's made up to date, and it was held over in Savisa.
Moved all the tables and chairs back, and the band played, and we danced.
Do you remember which band it was?

sure don't and this was i can look in here this was this is in spring spring probably april it was the weekend before combat ball i can remember that because we were worried about whether or not it would have any impact on the attendance now uh only fish and their dates came

right and then we had faculty advisors you did you have a special date you know i can't even remember having a date okay uh and what where did the girls uh that they came how did the how did the boys get a get connection with the tessies well uh most of them had been

one or two of them knew a girl that was going to TSCW and then she would get dates for everybody else in the outfit and they would come down a few of them had cars but most of them came on the bus and they would stay with faculty members here in the community I've been trying to remember if we had any motels I remember the Aggieland Inn but I don't remember whether there were
places other than homes for people to stay in.
And most of them stayed in homes.
And how did everybody behave at the dance?
It was fairly formal.
We were gentlemen.
You were a little bit intimidated, I can recall that, even as a senior.
It's probably about like the claims of drinking at Bonfire.
I don't remember that.
It wasn't evidenced.
Probably it did occur in some instances.
Could have been made a big story if it had been written about in today's media.
The young ladies were dressed in formal.
Yes, they were formally dressed.
The music was slow.
And you all didn't worry about somebody being intoxicated?
Never.
I don't ever remember anybody even smelling like liquor at dances here on campus.
And there were a lot of blind dates.

uh... probably ninety nine percent did now i've heard of beast buckets and moose pots does that ring a bell the guys would have a pot where you put money in and the afters all over who got the worst date got the money okay yeah pig pots pig pots pig pots and i've heard that the girls also had to say that the boys didn't know that probably didn't i wasn't aware of that
I've heard from two or three Tessies that they had the same.
But you always put those pots together before the girls got here.
And after you lost two or three pots, you quit betting on that.
The fun all was out of it.
What other big events were there for the freshman president to worry about?
That was it.
That and getting the organization for the Aggieland.

helping with the Aggieland staff and getting freshman pictures, making sure that everybody was in, getting enough freshman activities, because the freshmen participated like in intramurals separately from upperclassmen.
They had their own championships in swimming and wrestling and flag football, so the freshmen competed intramurally with other outfits freshmen.
So, uh,
That was more a part of the intramural officer in each unit to get those, that participation.
We worked with the Aggieland staff to get pictures of freshman activities athletically, units marching in, the freshman drill team, simply trying to make that class a part of A&M.
Turn back and describe Bonfire your freshman year.
What did y'all do and where did you?
We were red box.
We stacked.
Triple A had the responsibility of stacking.
Even as a freshman?
Yeah.
And about how long did y'all work on Bonfire?
From the SMU game, so about a month, six weeks.
And it always rained.
And, of course, it was always done by brute force.
And the stack area in those days was behind Duncan?
Yes.
Our first bonfire was in front of the MSC.
And then the rest of them were behind Duncan.
Why did they move it to Duncan?
I can't tell you.
I don't even remember why they moved it over there.
I always thought it was because of the fire hazard of

embers falling on campus building but you move it over there and it falls on the faculty Dr. Little lived about a block from the stack when they moved it to Duncan and he always spent that time when they lit it with a hose on top of his house spent all night watering down the house so that it wouldn't catch a fire
What did a fish red pot do?
We were on the ground with forked sticks.
They're called fuck sticks.
And we physically, by putting those sticks at an angle, physically put the logs up and wired them to the stack.
Didn't have any type of power equipment.
I never went to the cut area because our responsibility was to stack.
And we physically stacked it.
We took those logs and laid them up and our bonfire was 79 or 80 foot.
Back then, as you probably already know, the goal was to make it at least a foot taller than the year before.
So you knew how high you had to build it.
Do you remember how many stacks it was?
There was one.
You just took logs and put them up so that they were woven together and when you had hold you filled in with logs and there's no way that it could fall then because it wasn't separate units.
You'd put a tall log up and wire it up the top, and then you'd fill in.
Now, how did y'all get the logs way up there?
With a pulley.
Hooked to the... To the center pole.
To the center pole.
And they were just simply pullied up.
And about how many hours a night, a week, did you work?
Usually about eight.

eight hours on the stack a night yeah how many nights uh about every other night okay and you're still stacking was done 24 hours a day yeah because you had to in order to get it finished uh and was there any drinking around the stack area then uh do you remember i don't remember any drinking do you remember any injuries

of anybody anything no the cut area would frequently have people injured with axes and some of them serious but I don't remember any injuries on the stock area either a sprained hand or twisted an ankle or had a log that they didn't let go of quick enough and pulled a shoulder out of socket

but uh now you said serious in the cut area serious meaning what uh cut a leg halfway off or serious uh a flesh wound with an axe but they were mostly axe related and so you did this all four years yes and what did it change in your four years at all not really only the role that you played because uh the
all three AAA units, that was their responsibility.
I don't know how it became their responsibility.
I don't know the history on it.
All I knew is that we were responsible for stacking.
Freshmen were on the ground.
Sophomores ran the ground crew.
Juniors and seniors were up on the stack.
All right.
And they were responsible for the whole operation, stacking operation.
Was there a person, an individual, who was the chief of all chiefs for Bonfire?
Yeah.
Well, no, not for Bonfire, but for stacking there was.
A junior was selected as responsible, and I'm sure there was a senior above him, but you saw the junior was out there essentially 24 hours a day.
Did he have a nickname?
What was he?
I never heard it.
I wasn't it, so I don't know.
So there was not a commander-in-chief individual for Bonfire?
No.
Not that I ever was aware of.
Did civilian students work on Bonfire?
What are civilians?
No.
Well, I don't know because everyone, most people were in fatigues, but there were some people out there in jeans, particularly juniors and seniors.
Most people were in units.
You knew everybody, and they were from mostly AAA and field artillery.
were on the stack, but at the tail end when they had finished cutting, then a lot of people showed up to help finish the stack.
And you say it did not change during your four years.
Not significantly, it just got bigger each year.
And you all did wire everything together with cable?
No.
It was kind of like a
barbed wire with no barbed on it.
It was about that thick of wire.
Okay, okay.
And was there a myth about how long after the bonfire was lit?
It had to stay standing until the kickoff or we'd lose the game.
And most times it did stay up.
And most times under Bear Bryant we won the game.
Yeah.
But the myth was blown, though, in the 60s and 70s.
Yes.
Let's see.
Back to student government.
Okay, you were president of the freshman class.
Did you follow that up, sophomore, junior?
Student senate, yeah.
Student senate.
I was ag representative as a sophomore and I was vice chair of student senate as a junior and was student senate president.
And how did one become the vice chair and the president?
How did?
Those were selected by the student senate.
You ran campus-wide elections.
for the representative from the very school, and then for president of the student senate.
It was a campus-wide election.
Okay.
And do you remember who your opponent was, or opponents?
Joe Busser.
Joe Busser, again.
And how close was the final election?
It was close.
It was very competitive.
Were you and Joe friends?
Yes.
Competitors and friends.
What were the big issues
before the student senate your senior year?
We started the blood drive, the Aggie blood drive that year.
Don Rommel chaired Aggie.
Community Relations Committee and started the first Aggie Blood Drive.
Oh, describe that.
Well, we got with Wadley.
Whose idea was it?
It was either Don's or one of the committee members, but they took that on as their project for the year.
and they organized it and worked with Dean Penberthy on getting terms on the stipulations on how it would be handled and who would have access to the blood, etc.
But Don, you'll have to ask him.
Who?
I'm not sure.
Don Rummel.
Is he still?
He just retired as entomologist with the experiment station at Lubbock.
Where does he live?
Lubbock.
He retired on April 28th.
In fact, I was up just last week, last Friday night at his retirement party at the Lubbock National Bank.
And as you all understood it, the purpose of this blood drive was to raise blood for whom?
Aggies.
What kind of Aggies?
Students and former students.
And I can't remember the detail, but there had been some situations where people needed blood and were unable to get it after either accidents or surgery.
And how well did it go that first year?
Everybody went.
Everybody gave.
Do you remember where?
They were here a week.
And we're down in the basement next, had two or three rooms down there where the piano usually was.
Do you remember any poignant examples of where that blood was used in your experience?
No, not really.
I know two or three times I've asked, is it still operational the same way?
And we've put it in the Class of 59 newsletter.
All right, typist, you don't need to add this because this is personal, but I just want to share it.
This is back in the 70s, and one of my Garland elementary school buddies.
Now, I move away from Garland when I'm 10 years old.
He's an Aggie.
His name is Jack Leonard.
He was a dentist.
He would have been class of 52.
And he and I were close buddies growing up.
His dad was a dentist.
And I thought they were rich because they had two cars in the family.
And he called me and he said, I really need your help.
He said, you remember Gerald Cooper?
And I said, of course.
Gerald's mother and dad
And my mother and dad went to the movies together when the two young wives were pregnant.
Gerald's born a month ahead of me, but with awful hemophilia.
All his life.
And he was then, what would have, he'd been 50, I guess, 40, been 40.
And he said that he's in the hospital and they're having to give him two or three pints of blood a day.
And we have run out of all the friends and the relatives and everything.
Is it possible?
He said, I remember the Aggie, is it possible A&M could?
And I said, well, Gerald went to SMU, didn't he?
He said, yeah, but I was just wondering if maybe.
I said, well, let me check.
I feel a cold chill as I think about it.
So I called the student body president and told him the circumstances.
And this is not for an Aggie, but is it possible they might share some?
He called me back in an hour, and he said, would 500 pints be enough?
Well, you know, I have often wondered, and I've never followed up on it.
I haven't used it.
I don't know of anyone that has used it.
But when I have checked with Randy and them about the procedures, they said it's the same.
I think so.
It's available to any Aggie that needs it.
So that started while?
Start of 1959.
The first Aggie blood test.
collection by Wadley was in the spring of 59.
Were you, as the President of the Student Senate, were you photographed giving your blood?
No, I don't remember, but Rubble was.
That committee that put it together were highlighted.
What were some other big issues that you remember?
Well,
The co-ed issue was being talked about a little bit.
Really?
Summarize that.
Well, it was just rumors.
And, of course, all the students, most of the students, the ones that talked were absolutely opposed to women here at A&M.
What about those who didn't talk?

who knows did you have any opinion at that point I I yes I felt like that it wouldn't be a good thing to introduce women and to make A&M non-military I felt like that there was something very unique and different about this place and felt like that that would ruin it
Wasn't very vocal about that, but that was honestly my opinion.
Did reporters ever bug you about it, about your opinion?
No.
That was a little bit before it got actively being discussed.
Now, Mr. Rutter came here during your- He was vice president, vice chair.
Did you have any meetings with him, any conversations with him during that year you were president?
Some contact, but limited.
Most of my work was with Dean Penberthy.
Describe working with him.
He was a gentleman.
Dean Penney was good counsel.
He was a

very slow and deliberate in his discussing issues and topic with people he gave good support for the student government activities probably Wayne Stark was the one that was impressive from Stanford of being so formal and
hard-driving, totally different personalities.
Make believe I had never seen or met Wayne Stark.
Tell me about him.
Very formal, always dressed immaculately, very strictly business.
I found him a little bit out of place at this place.
A&M had a character about it that was different from the few formal places I had been in.
And Wayne was one that you would have expected to be in a very formal place.
Okay.
He was very well spoken.
It didn't take him long to say what he needed to say, and then he was gone.
When you went in, you knew you needed to have everything organized that you probably wouldn't have over three or four minutes.
Very effective.
Extremely well organized.
And very valuable once the students graduated.
He guided a lot of people in making good decisions.
Both while they were here, but also when they graduated.
He helped a lot of people make some very sound, lifelong decisions.
Did he ever give you any advice?
Not really.
You didn't seek him?
I didn't ask him for that kind of advice.
We got good, sound advice about who to approach to speak at Sconum.
and why, and how to approach them, whether you called or wrote and what you said and how you said it.
Those are the kinds of guidance that he provided.
Do you remember SCONA that year?
What was the topic and who were the speakers?
No, I never was chair of SCONA, but I worked on committees and organizing and putting it on.
Now, Stark occasionally gave a youngster a real serious lecture if he thought they were goofing off too much.
Did you ever get one of those lectures?
No, I didn't.
In fact, I was not aware that that happened.
Oh, called Green Couch Treatment.
He had this old green vinyl-covered couch.
He'd get you in there, close the door, and say, in effect, he'd say, you ought to be ashamed.
You can do better, and you know it, and I know it.
And by the time you got through, you felt about that high, and he'd say, now get out of here.
There were lots of people down here that could do that very well, all the way from sophomores to many of the faculty.
And I don't know if it was age or what, but...
There was a certain amount of fear and respect for faculty on this campus.
I know I was in awe of a lot of faculty members.
Such as?
Well, Mr. Reinhart, who taught taxonomy over in entomology, as a professor, he had a high expectation.
Don't ever try to
play games in his class or do things that might be fun.
Dr. James, who was head of the department, was very stiff and formal, and you just didn't want to have to do too much business with him when you were a student.
As a student body president, did you get to make any special trips?
Oh, yeah.
Such as?
Well, we went to the Cotton Bowl and at the SMU game got to tie Don Cloud's kiss of the Aggie sweetheart.
We made a number of multi-university governing conferences.
interacted with the other university's student government groups.
Which ones impressed you most?
Probably TU, which I hate to admit, but most of the Southwest Conference student leadership were good.
You were always impressed and felt like that you had to really strut in order to
make an equal impression among them.
I always was amazed at how much a uniform would do, really.
We'd go to conferences where, like the Texas State Science Fair, and it was just amazing at the difference in just putting on that A&M uniform.
Did you ever go to the legislature representing them?
Didn't even know we had one.

Because see, one of the things Jack Williams always did would be to take the student body president, the highest ranking woman, and the corps commander, and with a straight face he would say these students have been at random, just happened to run into them leaving the campus.
No.
Like the year that Fred McClure, you know Fred.
Yes, very well.
4-H kid from up in Henderson.
There you go.
And so Senator Aiken of Paris was chairman of the Senate Finance Committee during this era.
In old East Texas.
That's right.
So Jack Williams introduced Fred and he said,
And so Mr. Aiken said, Fred, tell these people where you're from.
Oh, I'm from St. Augustine, where...
He said, no, Fred, tell them where you were born and grew up.
Oh, that's right, sir.
I was born in Paris, your hometown.
Grew up there, and then we moved when I was a ninth grader.
In fact, this suit I'm wearing was...
